{"title":"PETRv2: A Unified Framework for 3D Perception from Multi-Camera Images","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Temporal alignment across frames in multi-camera 3D perception is challenging, especially for DETR-style methods like PETR that implicitly encode 3D position into 2D features and thus lack explicit feature warping.","method":"PETRv2 introduces 3D coordinates alignment (CA), transforming the 3D coordinates of the previous frame into the current frame’s coordinate system via pose transformation (using global coordinates as a bridge to compute T_{l(t)}^{l(t-1)}). The aligned 3D coordinates from frames t−1 and t are then used to generate position embeddings, and features/coordinates of adjacent frames are concatenated before decoding. This achieves temporal alignment through 3D PE rather than BEV feature warping and improves localization and velocity estimation (e.g., mAVE reduction)."},{"problem":"The original PETR 3D position embedding (3D PE) is data-independent, limiting adaptability and robustness because it does not leverage image content (e.g., depth cues).","method":"PETRv2 proposes a feature-guided position encoder (FPE) that makes 3D PE data-dependent. Projected 2D features are passed through a small MLP and Sigmoid to produce attention weights that reweight the MLP-transformed 3D coordinates element-wise, yielding feature-guided 3D PEs. The 3D PE is added to 2D features to form keys, while projected 2D features serve as values for the transformer decoder. This improves detection metrics and robustness to extrinsics noise over PETR and PETR+FPE baselines."},{"problem":"A unified framework for multi-task 3D perception (3D detection, BEV segmentation, 3D lane detection) from multi-camera images is needed without exploding query counts or changing architectures per task.","method":"PETRv2 introduces sparse, task-specific queries initialized in task-appropriate spaces and decoded by a shared transformer: det queries in 3D space as learnable anchors; seg queries in BEV space where each query corresponds to a BEV patch (e.g., 25×25); and lane queries defined as 3D anchor lanes using fixed sampling along the Y-axis, predicting class, offsets (Δx, Δz) from anchors, and a visibility vector. This unified sparse-query design supports high-resolution BEV segmentation and accurate 3D lanes while keeping global attention tractable, achieving state-of-the-art results across tasks."}]}
